1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:01,320
Meet Stan.

2
00:00:01,320 --> 00:00:04,120
This morning, Stan had one thing to do.

3
00:00:04,120 --> 00:00:05,440
Go for a run.

4
00:00:05,440 --> 00:00:06,480
That is it.

5
00:00:06,480 --> 00:00:08,920
One thing and all day to do it.

6
00:00:08,920 --> 00:00:10,440
He scrolled instead.

7
00:00:10,440 --> 00:00:11,680
He snacked.

8
00:00:11,680 --> 00:00:14,040
He told himself he would start in five minutes

9
00:00:14,040 --> 00:00:15,480
and now it is dark out.

10
00:00:15,480 --> 00:00:18,720
The run never happened and Stan is melted into the couch

11
00:00:18,720 --> 00:00:20,960
feeling like a complete failure.

12
00:00:20,960 --> 00:00:22,600
You know Stan.

13
00:00:22,600 --> 00:00:24,160
You might be Stan right now.

14
00:00:24,160 --> 00:00:28,760
So here's the twist for Stan and for you.

15
00:00:28,760 --> 00:00:31,400
That guilt he is feeling is the lie.

16
00:00:31,400 --> 00:00:32,960
Not the laziness.

17
00:00:32,960 --> 00:00:36,320
Stan is not broken and he is not weak.

18
00:00:36,320 --> 00:00:37,640
His brain is doing something it's

19
00:00:37,640 --> 00:00:40,760
spent a million years getting very, very good at.

20
00:00:40,760 --> 00:00:43,040
And the reason he feels so guilty about it

21
00:00:43,040 --> 00:00:46,840
traces back to a demon that a monk invented in the desert

22
00:00:46,840 --> 00:00:48,840
1600 years ago.

23
00:00:48,840 --> 00:00:50,640
Everybody knows this feeling.

24
00:00:50,640 --> 00:00:52,440
The task is right there.

25
00:00:52,440 --> 00:00:54,400
You even want to want to do it.

26
00:00:54,400 --> 00:00:56,600
And your body just will not launch.

27
00:00:56,600 --> 00:00:58,080
We call it laziness.

28
00:00:58,080 --> 00:01:00,680
And we treat it like a flaw in your character.

29
00:01:00,680 --> 00:01:03,920
But stop and ask the real question.

30
00:01:03,920 --> 00:01:07,760
Why would evolution build a creature that is bad at doing things?

31
00:01:07,760 --> 00:01:08,840
It wouldn't.

32
00:01:08,840 --> 00:01:11,240
What it actually built is a creature that is brilliant

33
00:01:11,240 --> 00:01:12,960
at not wasting energy.

34
00:01:12,960 --> 00:01:15,080
And those are not the same thing

35
00:01:15,080 --> 00:01:17,040
even though they feel like it.

36
00:01:17,040 --> 00:01:20,160
Because your brain underneath everything else it does

37
00:01:20,160 --> 00:01:21,880
is an energy accountant.

38
00:01:21,880 --> 00:01:24,480
For almost all of human history food was scarce

39
00:01:24,480 --> 00:01:26,120
and never guaranteed.

40
00:01:26,120 --> 00:01:28,160
Every calorie you burned was a calorie

41
00:01:28,160 --> 00:01:30,240
you might desperately need later.

42
00:01:30,240 --> 00:01:32,440
When a predator showed up or the next meal didn't,

43
00:01:32,440 --> 00:01:35,760
so your brain evolved one ruthless rule.

44
00:01:35,760 --> 00:01:38,360
Never spend effort you do not have to spend.

45
00:01:38,360 --> 00:01:40,960
Scientists call it the law of least effort.

46
00:01:40,960 --> 00:01:44,080
And it runs so deep you do not even notice it.

47
00:01:44,080 --> 00:01:46,520
When you walk across a room, your body

48
00:01:46,520 --> 00:01:48,680
is constantly making tiny adjustments

49
00:01:48,680 --> 00:01:51,040
to use the least energy possible.

50
00:01:51,040 --> 00:01:53,400
You are, right down to the cell,

51
00:01:53,400 --> 00:01:56,080
tuned to do as little as you can get away with.

52
00:01:56,080 --> 00:01:57,640
That is not a defect.

53
00:01:57,640 --> 00:02:00,640
That is the setting that kept your ancestors alive.

54
00:02:00,640 --> 00:02:04,600
So when Stan cannot make himself lace up those shoes,

55
00:02:04,600 --> 00:02:06,360
that is not weakness talking.

56
00:02:06,360 --> 00:02:09,120
That is his brain running a quiet calculation.

57
00:02:09,120 --> 00:02:11,240
The effort of the run on one side,

58
00:02:11,240 --> 00:02:12,800
the reward on the other,

59
00:02:12,800 --> 00:02:15,120
and the reward being a little healthier

60
00:02:15,120 --> 00:02:18,760
in some far off future is fuzzy and far away.

61
00:02:18,760 --> 00:02:22,920
So the brain votes, not worth it, and pulls the plug.

62
00:02:22,920 --> 00:02:25,920
The exact instinct that once stopped Stan's ancestors

63
00:02:25,920 --> 00:02:29,000
from wandering off and burning energy for no reason

64
00:02:29,000 --> 00:02:31,360
is the one gluing him to the couch tonight.

65
00:02:31,360 --> 00:02:32,960
The wiring is perfect.

66
00:02:32,960 --> 00:02:35,720
It just never got the memo that the danger is gone

67
00:02:35,720 --> 00:02:37,560
and the fridge is full.

68
00:02:37,560 --> 00:02:38,720
Okay.

69
00:02:38,720 --> 00:02:41,320
So if doing nothing is this natural,

70
00:02:41,320 --> 00:02:45,440
this built in, why on earth does it feel like a sin?

71
00:02:45,440 --> 00:02:48,960
Because strangely, it once literally was one.

72
00:02:48,960 --> 00:02:52,680
Rewind to the deserts of Egypt around the fourth century.

73
00:02:52,680 --> 00:02:54,600
Christian monks are living alone,

74
00:02:54,600 --> 00:02:57,400
trying to focus on God all day,

75
00:02:57,400 --> 00:03:01,440
and they keep getting ambushed by a very specific enemy.

76
00:03:01,440 --> 00:03:03,960
It hits in the heat of the afternoon,

77
00:03:03,960 --> 00:03:06,760
a heavy, restless, hollow feeling

78
00:03:06,760 --> 00:03:10,800
where you cannot care about anything and cannot sit still.

79
00:03:10,800 --> 00:03:13,640
They gave it a name, acedia,

80
00:03:13,640 --> 00:03:16,480
and they called it the noonday demon.

81
00:03:16,480 --> 00:03:18,800
A monk named Evagrius wrote it down

82
00:03:18,800 --> 00:03:22,360
as one of the eight great temptations of the human soul.

83
00:03:22,360 --> 00:03:23,680
A couple of centuries later,

84
00:03:23,680 --> 00:03:27,040
the church tidied that list of eight down to seven.

85
00:03:27,040 --> 00:03:29,760
Acedia got folded in and given a new name.

86
00:03:29,760 --> 00:03:34,760
One you already know, sloth, one of the seven deadly sins.

87
00:03:35,000 --> 00:03:38,080
So sit with that for a second.

88
00:03:38,080 --> 00:03:41,280
The very first time anyone declared not feeling like it

89
00:03:41,280 --> 00:03:44,600
to be evil, it had nothing to do with work or chores.

90
00:03:44,600 --> 00:03:48,120
It was a spiritual demon that haunted monks at lunchtime.

91
00:03:48,120 --> 00:03:51,640
For a long time, that is all it was, a religious idea.

92
00:03:51,640 --> 00:03:54,160
Then came the part that actually planted the guilt

93
00:03:54,160 --> 00:03:55,680
in your chest today.

94
00:03:55,680 --> 00:03:57,760
As workshops turned into factories,

95
00:03:57,760 --> 00:03:59,920
a powerful new idea took hold.

96
00:03:59,920 --> 00:04:05,080
That hard work itself was holy and idle time was wasted time.

97
00:04:05,080 --> 00:04:09,440
Stolen from God and very conveniently from your boss.

98
00:04:09,440 --> 00:04:11,640
Clocks went up on the walls, living to work

99
00:04:11,640 --> 00:04:13,840
became a virtue you could brag about.

100
00:04:13,840 --> 00:04:16,320
And resting got quietly rebranded

101
00:04:16,320 --> 00:04:20,760
from a normal thing every human does into a moral failure.

102
00:04:20,760 --> 00:04:22,560
That judgment never left.

103
00:04:22,560 --> 00:04:24,920
Every time you feel guilty for doing nothing,

104
00:04:24,920 --> 00:04:29,080
you are feeling the echo of a few hundred year old sales pitch.

105
00:04:29,080 --> 00:04:32,040
So here's the quiet truth underneath all of it.

106
00:04:32,040 --> 00:04:34,000
There is nothing wrong with you.

107
00:04:34,000 --> 00:04:38,400
Two things are colliding inside you and neither one is a flaw.

108
00:04:38,400 --> 00:04:41,480
The first is an ancient, genuinely brilliant instinct

109
00:04:41,480 --> 00:04:42,960
to conserve energy.

110
00:04:42,960 --> 00:04:47,280
The thing that carried humans through 100,000 years of scarcity.

111
00:04:47,280 --> 00:04:49,400
The second is a much newer idea that says

112
00:04:49,440 --> 00:04:51,360
that instinct is shameful.

113
00:04:51,360 --> 00:04:53,040
You are not lazy.

114
00:04:53,040 --> 00:04:55,720
You are a finely tuned survival machine

115
00:04:55,720 --> 00:04:57,880
being graded by a rule book that was written

116
00:04:57,880 --> 00:04:59,840
to keep factories running.

117
00:04:59,840 --> 00:05:03,000
Which means lazy was never really one thing.

118
00:05:04,280 --> 00:05:06,760
Sometimes it is your brain correctly telling you

119
00:05:06,760 --> 00:05:08,960
the reward is not worth the effort.

120
00:05:08,960 --> 00:05:12,080
And honestly, that one is worth listening to.

121
00:05:12,080 --> 00:05:14,440
And sometimes it is a task that looks enormous

122
00:05:14,440 --> 00:05:16,240
to your energy saving brain,

123
00:05:16,240 --> 00:05:18,760
but is actually small once you are moving

124
00:05:18,760 --> 00:05:21,480
because the first step always costs the most

125
00:05:21,480 --> 00:05:23,400
and your inner accountant charges you

126
00:05:23,400 --> 00:05:25,720
for the whole journey up front.

127
00:05:25,720 --> 00:05:28,640
The fix was never to shame yourself harder.

128
00:05:28,640 --> 00:05:30,680
It is to shrink that first step

129
00:05:30,680 --> 00:05:33,040
until the accountant stops objecting.

130
00:05:33,040 --> 00:05:34,800
You are not fighting a weakness.

131
00:05:34,800 --> 00:05:38,760
You are negotiating with a very old, very stubborn instinct.

132
00:05:38,760 --> 00:05:40,960
So the next time it is you on that couch,

133
00:05:40,960 --> 00:05:44,640
the run not done, that little voice calling you lazy,

134
00:05:44,640 --> 00:05:46,720
you will know what is really happening.

135
00:05:46,720 --> 00:05:48,560
A million year old survival instinct

136
00:05:48,560 --> 00:05:51,440
just ran into a few hundred year old guilt trip

137
00:05:51,440 --> 00:05:54,600
and you like Stan got caught in the middle.

138
00:05:54,600 --> 00:05:56,080
You were never broken.

139
00:05:56,080 --> 00:05:59,240
You have just been running very, very old software.

140
00:05:59,240 --> 00:06:02,000
And now, at least, you know who wrote it.
